   <h2>   What is metadata?</h2>

   <p>
   Metadata is information describing a resource or collection of resources contained within ScholarSphere. This includes descriptive information (about the actual content of the object and the persons or entities responsible for it); technical metadata (about the file format, preservation actions taken on the resources), and administrative metadata (use restrictions or other copyright and licensing information, etc.). 
  </p>

  <h2>Why should I pay attention to creating metadata?</h2>

  <p>
   Metadata allows users to discover your content through searching on a number of different aspects of it -- subject search, author/creator search, format search, etc. It also allows content contributors to track the content they or others have submitted, i.e. files related to a grant-funded project, or about a particular topic of interest.
   </p>

   <h2>How is metadata created in ScholarSphere at the point of submission and ingest?</h2>

   <p>
   Two ways: auto-generation by the system (dates uploaded or modified, file size, etc.) , and contribution of metadata content by users( subject or keywords, creator names, notes.)  Metadata can be added to materials already in ScholarSphere.
    </p>
  
